1
00:00:00,335 --> 00:00:24,756
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambudasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambudasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambudasa

2
00:00:26,085 --> 00:00:30,210
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:38,320 --> 00:00:54,219
So the last time I spoke it was about the bit where the Buddha becomes enlightened and is attacked by Mara and then eventually overcomes that attack and becomes liberated.

4
00:00:54,942 --> 00:01:01,051
So what I mean to do is just go back a little bit and really discuss this fellow Mara.

5
00:01:02,533 --> 00:01:04,617
So there were nine storms.

6
00:01:06,180 --> 00:01:12,969
The wind, the rain, the rocks, the missiles, the embers, the ashes, the sand, the mud and the darkness.

7
00:01:15,174 --> 00:01:17,878
And when they approached the Buddha or the Bodhisattva,

8
00:01:18,617 --> 00:01:25,084
He was either untouched or they turned into garlands, flowers, sandalwood powder, barns and light.

9
00:01:27,546 --> 00:01:33,612
So these of course refer to hindrances or what's called hindrances.

10
00:01:35,534 --> 00:01:40,640
And the Buddha's own image for these hindrances are like a pool of water.

11
00:01:41,320 --> 00:01:43,082
So the mind is like a pool of water.

12
00:01:44,004 --> 00:01:48,067
And if it's discoloured with all various different colours

13
00:01:48,165 --> 00:01:51,149
kaleidoscopic, then you can't see into it.

14
00:01:51,969 --> 00:01:55,272
You can't see into it because you're enchanted by these colours.

15
00:01:56,453 --> 00:02:01,599
If the water's boiling, then that's an image of hatred and anger.

16
00:02:02,881 --> 00:02:08,507
If it's covered over with mosses, that's the effect of dullness and lethargy.

17
00:02:08,526 --> 00:02:13,752
And if the wind blows across the pool and makes the waves, then that's an image of restlessness.

18
00:02:14,439 --> 00:02:19,788
And if it's turbid and muddy, that's the insidious pervasiveness of doubt.

19
00:02:21,450 --> 00:02:25,717
That's the Buddha being a little poetic.

20
00:02:28,622 --> 00:02:37,157
But for us, the defilements when they arise are to be acknowledged as our trainers.

21
00:02:38,453 --> 00:02:40,175
They must be embraced as friends.

22
00:02:40,596 --> 00:02:44,420
They've come to help us to develop our perfections.

23
00:02:47,525 --> 00:02:54,033
And we can say that the greater the defilement, the greater the potential for perfection.

24
00:02:56,236 --> 00:02:59,140
The more horrible you are, the more wonderful you'll become.

25
00:03:00,763 --> 00:03:03,687
So there's hope even for people like Hitler and Stalin.

26
00:03:04,828 --> 00:03:06,250
Heavens, they might become Buddhists.

27
00:03:08,913 --> 00:03:15,264
One of the things when we hit these hindrances is that we don't know our virtues until they're tested.

28
00:03:16,548 --> 00:03:24,002
And I'm reminded of a book I read many years ago by a man called Brian Keener who was an Irish fellow and he

29
00:03:24,201 --> 00:03:54,056
was one of the many who got kidnapped in Lebanon during that time and his book An Evil Cradling is well worth reading because he really went through some horrible stuff and I heard an interview with him and the usual question was you must be very strong to undergo these things you must have had a tremendous power inside you and he insisted that it wasn't so and that other people found similar strengths

30
00:03:54,442 --> 00:04:06,165
I mean, there were one or two who broke down, who broke, but generally speaking, we have this inner virtue which we don't know until we're tested.

31
00:04:06,186 --> 00:04:14,323
So when these defilements come up, we have to see them as testers, trainers, teachers, friends.

32
00:04:17,509 --> 00:04:25,019
What I want to do rather than go through them in the usual order is just take the ones that we normally suffer from.

33
00:04:25,038 --> 00:04:30,906
And I want to do it for a little while and then I want to answer these questions.

34
00:04:32,187 --> 00:04:37,973
The question sheet that I put up didn't get filled very quickly.

35
00:04:39,036 --> 00:04:41,137
So most of the questions come from people who've left.

36
00:04:41,826 --> 00:04:48,016
So I'm hoping that I can sort of telepathically send it to them as I speak.

37
00:04:51,060 --> 00:04:56,850
So the first big one, isn't it, that we hit usually when we come to retreat is the old dullness and lethargy.

38
00:04:58,432 --> 00:05:01,415
The old sloth and topo, you know.

39
00:05:01,437 --> 00:05:04,802
And we have to understand why it is that we have so much of it.

40
00:05:05,762 --> 00:05:11,091
So the first reason is, of course, that we like sleeping.

41
00:05:12,690 --> 00:05:22,947
We indulge in it, Sunday morning, rollover, cup of tea, newspaper, roll back over, the beach, say no more.

42
00:05:24,288 --> 00:05:37,129
So all these times that we have longed to sleep, to rest, for no reason at all apart from that it's a sweet thing to do.

43
00:05:39,151 --> 00:05:42,694
builds up that conditioning of seeking happiness in oblivion.

44
00:05:44,297 --> 00:05:44,838
That's what we're doing.

45
00:05:45,718 --> 00:05:49,603
And the fact of the matter is that in oblivion there is no suffering.

46
00:05:51,865 --> 00:05:52,187
Correct?

47
00:05:53,908 --> 00:05:54,689
There's no suffering.

48
00:05:56,372 --> 00:05:57,673
In oblivion there's no suffering.

49
00:05:59,074 --> 00:06:03,560
It's only when you wake up that you realise that it hasn't worked.

50
00:06:06,283 --> 00:06:07,925
But the other reason that we...

51
00:06:08,547 --> 00:06:14,194
tend to fall asleep, is of course that we're turning away from something, we're pushing something away.

52
00:06:15,036 --> 00:06:18,180
So we feel depressed, we feel down, we feel a bit anxious.

53
00:06:18,961 --> 00:06:21,184
And you just lay out on the couch and off you go.

54
00:06:22,505 --> 00:06:26,471
And here are the two great tanhas, the two great cravings.

55
00:06:26,810 --> 00:06:32,478
The craving of bhava, the craving of becoming, so we want to become oblivious to the world.

56
00:06:33,319 --> 00:06:40,247
And vibhavartana, the craving to annihilate ourselves, which takes us towards suicide.

57
00:06:42,310 --> 00:07:00,610
So, when we understand that these are at the root of our problem, then at least we have some basis in which to really argue with ourselves, to really confront these feelings when they come up, no matter how heavy they are.

58
00:07:02,125 --> 00:07:06,050
Now, there's a story of Moggallana.

59
00:07:06,071 --> 00:07:13,523
Moggallana had just met the Buddha and, not surprisingly, the big thing that he suffered from was sloth and torpor.

60
00:07:14,425 --> 00:07:19,432
So he went to the Buddha and the Buddha gave him nine things to do.

61
00:07:21,136 --> 00:07:28,166
He said, first of all, when the first sign comes, he said, take no notice, just lift the spine, put more energy into the practice.

62
00:07:30,154 --> 00:07:33,497
If you're still coming, then consider the Dharma.

63
00:07:33,517 --> 00:07:35,038
Recognise the danger of the hindrance.

64
00:07:35,139 --> 00:07:38,341
Build up some wholesome fear, you might say.

65
00:07:38,562 --> 00:07:39,783
A dread of consequences.

66
00:07:40,363 --> 00:07:41,584
And that should lift a bit of energy.

67
00:07:43,607 --> 00:07:48,151
If that doesn't work, recite the Dharma.

68
00:07:48,170 --> 00:07:53,877
Now, if you don't know any Dharma, then you can recite anything, just to keep you awake.

69
00:07:54,197 --> 00:07:57,579
This is an effort just to keep awake, remember.

70
00:07:59,752 --> 00:08:01,596
Then he said, if that doesn't work, rub your ears.

71
00:08:03,237 --> 00:08:04,839
So he must have known about acupuncture points.

72
00:08:06,682 --> 00:08:08,165
And if that doesn't work, he said, rub your legs.

73
00:08:10,567 --> 00:08:13,451
And if that doesn't work, get up and wash your face in cold water.

74
00:08:14,853 --> 00:08:18,117
And if that fails, he said, open your eyes.

75
00:08:18,738 --> 00:08:22,824
You must have opened your eyes before, but somewhere along the line you can open your eyes.

76
00:08:23,141 --> 00:08:26,245
And then if that doesn't work, you can create a light source in your mind.

77
00:08:26,946 --> 00:08:30,569
Only people who have practiced jhana, I should think, can do that.

78
00:08:31,050 --> 00:08:32,691
And then finally, walk up and down.

79
00:08:33,792 --> 00:08:38,496
Now, the thing here is that what he's saying is don't give up easy.

80
00:08:39,238 --> 00:08:48,947
He's given nine different ways in which to overcome, try to work against that desire to fall asleep.

81
00:08:49,754 --> 00:08:53,116
Now in terms of our practice, we can simplify that.

82
00:08:53,136 --> 00:08:59,724
So yes, when those first feelings come, you have to recognise them fairly quickly and just lift up the body.

83
00:08:59,764 --> 00:09:00,504
Sometimes they go.

84
00:09:00,965 --> 00:09:05,509
It's just a bit of not enough energy around and it's just moving us towards sleep.

85
00:09:09,274 --> 00:09:11,897
Then if that doesn't work, just open your eyes, let a bit of light in.

86
00:09:14,058 --> 00:09:16,461
The other one that I've tried is hands on your head.

87
00:09:16,660 --> 00:09:18,003
Not on top of your head, it hurts your neck.

88
00:09:18,482 --> 00:09:19,203
Something like that.

89
00:09:19,673 --> 00:09:22,677
You ever tried that?

90
00:09:22,697 --> 00:09:23,339
It sort of works.

91
00:09:25,322 --> 00:09:28,527
Of course, if it fails, you tend to move forward pretty quickly.

92
00:09:29,027 --> 00:09:30,929
It would be dangerous.

93
00:09:31,451 --> 00:09:33,293
But generally speaking, you sort of catch yourself.

94
00:09:35,136 --> 00:09:36,538
Then, if that doesn't work, you stand up.

95
00:09:37,701 --> 00:09:42,447
And if you feel you're going to fall over, then you have to walk.

96
00:09:42,467 --> 00:09:45,613
Now, when you walk, don't do the slow walking meditation.

97
00:09:46,386 --> 00:09:48,428
What you want to do is just gently walk up and down.

98
00:09:48,788 --> 00:09:53,653
Because what we're trying to do is refuse to fall into that temptation.

99
00:09:54,134 --> 00:10:00,260
Whatever the rule is, whatever the hindrance is telling us to do, we must do exactly the opposite.

100
00:10:00,280 --> 00:10:04,885
So if these hindrances are saying, look, fall asleep, have a little kip, a power nap, that's what you need.

101
00:10:06,206 --> 00:10:08,629
And you say, no way, I know you, Mara.

102
00:10:09,910 --> 00:10:12,072
That's the mud that he threw at the Buddha.

103
00:10:13,589 --> 00:10:15,211
And you stand up against it, you won't do it.

104
00:10:16,331 --> 00:10:18,054
You have to resist, no matter what.

105
00:10:19,475 --> 00:10:20,356
And you don't fight it.

106
00:10:20,376 --> 00:10:26,144
If you find yourself fighting it, of course, then you're pushing a lot of turbulence back into the system.

107
00:10:26,764 --> 00:10:29,369
Then it becomes a struggle and you just get a headache.

108
00:10:31,071 --> 00:10:34,235
So it's a case of just being with it, of allowing it to be there.

109
00:10:36,677 --> 00:10:42,465
When you walk, when you walk up and down with it, for instance, just imagine you're just taking a big fat dog for a walk.

110
00:10:43,272 --> 00:10:44,732
He's dragging it with you, that's all.

111
00:10:44,754 --> 00:10:46,294
Come on, come on.

112
00:10:48,017 --> 00:10:54,202
Now, you can go to extreme levels to overcome sloth and torpor.

113
00:10:54,683 --> 00:11:04,974
There's a story, and I can't remember where I picked it up from, where a monk was rather desperate about it all, and he sat against a pole and sort of tied his head to it.

114
00:11:06,875 --> 00:11:08,197
Unfortunately, he fell asleep.

115
00:11:09,197 --> 00:11:10,779
When they came in, they thought he'd hanged himself.

116
00:11:10,820 --> 00:11:12,721
He's actually fallen asleep.

117
00:11:14,643 --> 00:11:19,226
The other thing you can try is to sit near a wall.

118
00:11:21,408 --> 00:11:28,355
And when you go forward, you definitely wake up with that last little crack on the head.

119
00:11:29,336 --> 00:11:33,740
Unfortunately, as I found anyway, it doesn't seem to help very much.

120
00:11:33,759 --> 00:11:35,361
You've got very strong torpor.

121
00:11:35,381 --> 00:11:42,607
You do wake up, as it were, but then eventually, if it's really bad, your body does tend to collapse and you really knock the wall.

122
00:11:43,447 --> 00:11:47,092
And after a week of this, I got this feeling there was a bit of brain damage going on.

123
00:11:48,475 --> 00:11:49,416
I sort of gave up on it.

124
00:11:50,518 --> 00:11:59,149
But when I got to my cootie, my hut, I found that I used to sit under a net, a mosquito net.

125
00:11:59,169 --> 00:12:07,942
I used to find that just that, just that little touch on the head from the mosquito net was enough to just keep me up.

126
00:12:07,962 --> 00:12:09,625
These are only suggestions, you understand.

127
00:12:15,528 --> 00:12:36,134
I was at a retreat years ago and a big tall man was standing next to me and we were meditating and this almighty crash he had actually fallen over, he had keeled over so there's a sort of you have to use a bit of common sense somewhere when we went over to help him he refused to be helped

128
00:12:37,886 --> 00:12:42,952
And there was another occasion when this was when I was a lay person.

129
00:12:42,972 --> 00:12:45,056
There was another occasion when I was a monk.

130
00:12:45,076 --> 00:12:48,559
I was in Penang and they've got a beautiful centre there.

131
00:12:50,482 --> 00:12:55,229
And this young monk, he was a German fellow, very tall, big fellow.

132
00:12:55,249 --> 00:12:59,494
And he would get up with us at two o'clock, would you believe, to do the meditation.

133
00:12:59,614 --> 00:13:01,657
And he'd do walking meditation at the back of the hall.

134
00:13:02,859 --> 00:13:05,581
And there was this, again, this enormous crash

135
00:13:06,541 --> 00:13:07,861
And he'd walked into a painting.

136
00:13:09,583 --> 00:13:12,648
It was lucky it wasn't a window.

137
00:13:12,668 --> 00:13:13,369
Very embarrassed.

138
00:13:13,389 --> 00:13:14,509
None of us got up, by the way.

139
00:13:14,549 --> 00:13:16,111
We all just noted here and here.

140
00:13:21,518 --> 00:13:25,282
So, obviously, you have to use a bit of common sense with these things.

141
00:13:28,065 --> 00:13:28,846
But what do you do?

142
00:13:29,285 --> 00:13:32,710
What do you actually do when these things come, you see?

143
00:13:33,029 --> 00:13:34,471
I mean, what's the practice there?

144
00:13:34,975 --> 00:13:36,836
So it's to investigate it, isn't it?

145
00:13:36,976 --> 00:13:46,629
So first of all, there's usually that reaction to it, the aversion, the not wanting it, the want to shake yourself out of it, go for a brisk walk.

146
00:13:46,729 --> 00:13:49,631
See, now if you do that, you're suppressing it.

147
00:13:49,652 --> 00:13:56,721
If you think you can kick this out of the way by walking up and down fast, then there's a possibility that actually all you're doing is pushing it away.

148
00:13:56,900 --> 00:14:02,147
So that pushing it away re-enters the system and then you get more swell, more torpor.

149
00:14:04,051 --> 00:14:14,807
So, when we're sitting there and this stuff comes, there may be that desire to go there, so that's the pleasure, and there may be that resistance to it, not wanting to deal with it.

150
00:14:17,409 --> 00:14:27,304
But frankly, of all the painful mental states that we have, you know, depression, anxiety and all that, this isn't so bad, is it?

151
00:14:28,546 --> 00:14:31,370
I mean, I'm alright with it.

152
00:14:31,571 --> 00:14:33,754
Gentle, fuzzy feelings in the head,

153
00:14:34,325 --> 00:14:39,711
Sometimes it gets a bit like porridge, but you just... And what the idea is that you sort of wander about.

154
00:14:40,913 --> 00:14:43,176
If you keep your attention moving, it'll keep you awake.

155
00:14:43,956 --> 00:14:47,522
You just wander about, feeling this, feeling that, around the middle of your head.

156
00:14:48,222 --> 00:14:52,388
And then maybe you can come out of your head and see if there's any dullness, any lethargy anywhere else.

157
00:14:54,390 --> 00:15:01,480
If there's a bright, if the mind is bright, but the body feels very lethargic, you move around, just feeling here, feeling there.

158
00:15:02,219 --> 00:15:04,022
Just wondering if your big toe feels lethargic.

159
00:15:04,042 --> 00:15:09,350
Have you ever investigated that?

160
00:15:09,370 --> 00:15:09,509
See?

161
00:15:10,010 --> 00:15:18,023
And it's just keeping that consciousness moving, just keeping the attention moving, just gives it that little bit of energy not to be drawn into it.

162
00:15:18,043 --> 00:15:23,672
And what we're investigating, as always, is the quality of those sensations, those feelings.

163
00:15:24,552 --> 00:15:30,522
Now we can see them from the three characteristics point of view, you know, the fact that they're constantly a course of change,

164
00:15:30,788 --> 00:15:36,897
When you're looking at it, the observer can't be the observed, there must be some sort of distance, so it's not me, not I.

165
00:15:37,817 --> 00:15:43,066
And again that reaction of wanting, not wanting, which is the dukkha, the suffering.

166
00:15:43,086 --> 00:15:50,636
But you can also look at it more in terms of the four great elements.

167
00:15:51,528 --> 00:16:00,821
Try and feel it's, sometimes it's, we haven't got words for these things, it's all a featheriness, it's lightness, it's dustiness.

168
00:16:01,601 --> 00:16:02,823
And just get into it, you know.

169
00:16:03,144 --> 00:16:12,077
If words don't come, if you're using the noting technique and words don't come, don't bother with it, just feel what's actually happening there, actually get into it.

170
00:16:14,321 --> 00:16:15,942
And that's what we're doing, that's all we're doing.

171
00:16:16,243 --> 00:16:19,408
And in so doing, remember, we're always allowing

172
00:16:19,860 --> 00:16:27,038
this turbulence, because it's a turbulence, it's an energy, to expend itself, to just blow itself out.

173
00:16:28,523 --> 00:16:36,283
Now every time we fall into it, remember, even when we don't want to, even if we don't want to, even if we do it totally unwittingly,

174
00:16:36,668 --> 00:16:39,312
There's always that little moment of impulsion.

175
00:16:39,913 --> 00:16:40,815
Remember that.

176
00:16:40,934 --> 00:16:46,985
Whenever we fall into some dream, fantasy or whatever, there's always that little moment of impulsion.

177
00:16:47,004 --> 00:16:47,905
And that's the chaitanya.

178
00:16:48,167 --> 00:16:48,768
That's the will.

179
00:16:49,168 --> 00:16:54,616
And it's recreating and continues to create and continues to reinforce that conditioning.

180
00:16:55,138 --> 00:17:01,128
Now, it's not a powerful thing, but it's there.

181
00:17:01,327 --> 00:17:03,672
It's there constantly pushing that wheel round.

182
00:17:05,086 --> 00:17:13,615
So when we know that, then of course we get that feeling of putting a little bit of special effort into that practice.

183
00:17:15,336 --> 00:17:17,317
These things can last a long time, you know.

184
00:17:18,839 --> 00:17:20,020
They can last for days.

185
00:17:21,563 --> 00:17:22,743
So you just have to bear with it.

186
00:17:23,704 --> 00:17:27,407
I mean, it's not as though it's like that all the time, but it can be sort of hanging around.

187
00:17:28,348 --> 00:17:33,034
And it feels as though you can't investigate anything because it feels so dull.

188
00:17:33,807 --> 00:17:37,411
But that's because you're not making the dullness something to investigate.

189
00:17:38,672 --> 00:17:45,598
And if boredom comes, you note that, because that's coming out of a desire for pleasure, a desire for some sort of happiness or distraction.

190
00:17:46,559 --> 00:17:48,422
You just keep going back to it, keep going back to it.

191
00:17:48,903 --> 00:17:58,613
And remind ourselves that when these things come up, in that way, as physical feelings, they're actually exhausting themselves.

192
00:17:58,792 --> 00:18:02,717
That's how the conditioning exhausts itself.

193
00:18:04,232 --> 00:18:17,611
Now often when we do this with these feelings it might be that as they begin to disappear whatever has been suppressed begins to arise.

194
00:18:19,113 --> 00:18:28,226
It might be fear, it might be anything down there.

195
00:18:28,246 --> 00:18:31,911
So the resolution then is to refuse to be annihilated.

196
00:18:35,182 --> 00:18:39,708
And with all these hindrances, remember, that's the purification of the heart.

197
00:18:39,728 --> 00:18:40,809
So that's an energy.

198
00:18:41,510 --> 00:18:45,036
And when it's released, it's transformed.

199
00:18:45,256 --> 00:18:46,336
It doesn't stop.

200
00:18:46,457 --> 00:18:50,603
The energy isn't dissipated or lost.

201
00:18:51,163 --> 00:18:57,472
Remember that in right attitude of the Eightfold Path, hatred turns to love, cruelty to compassion.

202
00:18:57,633 --> 00:18:59,214
So there's a transformation going on.

203
00:18:59,548 --> 00:19:05,680
And this energy now, purified of that tightness, is there to be used.

204
00:19:06,181 --> 00:19:12,330
And it'll come back into the awareness, it'll come back into all the factors of enlightenment.

205
00:19:14,535 --> 00:19:17,440
So it's really worth struggling with it.

206
00:19:18,414 --> 00:19:30,371
You know, it's up to you as to how much you want to find out where the point of tiredness is and the point of lethargy, this dullness and lethargy starts.

207
00:19:31,251 --> 00:19:44,209
So, if after, say, on a retreat, if after three days you've sort of settled in and you feel settled and you're sleeping something like seven hours, you see, push it back a bit, go back to five and a half.

208
00:19:44,869 --> 00:19:47,393
Remember, we sleep in these one and three quarter hour patterns.

209
00:19:47,557 --> 00:20:17,328
and then when you do that of course you have to go through three days of misery to get that energy up but in so doing you see something may be being released because we don't know how much of our so called sleep is actually needed and then when that's settled and you're actually flying along on five and a half hours and you feel generally ok with it not that these feelings won't come up push it back a bit more so you can get back to four hours three and a half you see

210
00:20:17,646 --> 00:20:18,828
and give it another three days.

211
00:20:19,790 --> 00:20:26,242
If you can do that, lift it up three days, then, you know, really, it's very difficult to go back beyond that.

212
00:20:27,005 --> 00:20:29,249
Even the Buddha needed two hours.

213
00:20:29,269 --> 00:20:34,298
And on a hot day, on the hot season, you have to have a kip in the afternoon too.

214
00:20:34,318 --> 00:20:39,147
So it's not as though we want to do without sleep, but we just want to find out how much sleep do we actually need.

215
00:20:39,549 --> 00:20:53,164
Now, if you knock it back to three and a half hours, four hours, and after four to five days you're still falling all over the place and crashing through doors and things like that, then you come back forward again and try five and a half hours.

216
00:20:53,184 --> 00:20:58,150
And then you know where the line is as far as this retreat is concerned.

217
00:20:59,171 --> 00:21:04,376
That's not an all-time rule, that's just this moment, this retreat, this is what I can handle.

218
00:21:05,436 --> 00:21:09,401
And in so doing, you're actually gently pushing the system, you see.

219
00:21:09,421 --> 00:21:12,484
You're gently, shall we say, squeezing the pimple.

220
00:21:15,127 --> 00:21:17,971
You've got to give it a little squeeze and it'll pop, see.

221
00:21:17,990 --> 00:21:22,516
So you've got to work with it a little bit.

222
00:21:23,896 --> 00:21:28,742
So that sort of gives us some idea about sort and talk.

223
00:21:29,343 --> 00:21:33,688
I do prefer the words doneness and lethargy, but I'm used to saying sort and talk more.

224
00:21:35,660 --> 00:21:46,931
If while you're listening you come up with some question or you come up with a technique which has never been known before but which works for you do leave me a little note please because I'm collecting techniques.

225
00:21:47,132 --> 00:21:52,156
It's my job.

226
00:21:52,176 --> 00:21:56,740
So now opposite to that is all these feelings of restlessness.

227
00:21:58,903 --> 00:22:03,387
So again when we look at the root cause the root cause of restlessness

228
00:22:04,464 --> 00:22:06,487
So it's all part of our indulgence, isn't it?

229
00:22:06,827 --> 00:22:11,773
Rushing here, rushing there, getting this done, getting that done, wanting this, wanting that.

230
00:22:11,794 --> 00:22:16,920
I mean the whole society is in a sort of constant rush.

231
00:22:17,800 --> 00:22:22,385
So we're in that flow of getting things done in order to achieve something.

232
00:22:22,405 --> 00:22:27,952
So there's that pleasure that comes with doing something fast and achieving something.

233
00:22:31,116 --> 00:22:33,138
One very good exercise you might try

234
00:22:33,675 --> 00:23:00,003
is just because this is also a lot to do with our relationship to time and time passing and everybody has slightly different relationships to time psychological time and one little trick you can do which definitely helped me was to get a clock with fingers and just sit there watching it two hours

235
00:23:00,490 --> 00:23:02,031
Just watching the clock go round.

236
00:23:02,732 --> 00:23:05,237
And just listen to what comes up.

237
00:23:05,257 --> 00:23:07,380
And all this stuff about wasting time.

238
00:23:07,420 --> 00:23:08,741
What are you doing here?

239
00:23:08,761 --> 00:23:10,285
You should be out there doing something.

240
00:23:10,724 --> 00:23:12,448
And you just sit there just watching it go round.

241
00:23:13,950 --> 00:23:15,251
Minute after minute.

242
00:23:15,271 --> 00:23:16,513
And the passage of time.

243
00:23:17,634 --> 00:23:19,117
The fact that we can't control it.

244
00:23:19,357 --> 00:23:23,483
All sorts of stuff comes up.

245
00:23:23,503 --> 00:23:24,726
The office can buy you a clock.

246
00:23:27,862 --> 00:23:31,367
Now the other reason of course that we rush is that we are pushing things away.

247
00:23:32,849 --> 00:23:36,736
We don't want to look at certain things so we're running in the opposite direction.

248
00:23:37,778 --> 00:23:45,288
Often for instance when we feel depressed we'll force ourselves, you know the old kick in the you know what and get going.

249
00:23:45,990 --> 00:23:52,421
And unfortunately we do that only by way of not looking at something which is unpleasant.

250
00:23:52,441 --> 00:23:55,184
We're running away from it so it's a form of aversion.

251
00:23:56,178 --> 00:23:58,842
And when we do that we are against the pressing.

252
00:23:58,882 --> 00:24:10,778
So when we slow down and that's one of the great things about slowing down so that you can feel that impulse to rush, rush, rush, move, move, move.

253
00:24:11,941 --> 00:24:23,518
And if you just stop and just stay with that then often when that begins to dissipate an underlying feeling, an underlying mental state

254
00:24:23,785 --> 00:24:26,589
which it's been actually suppressing begins to arise.

255
00:24:33,140 --> 00:24:41,253
And interestingly enough, this particular hindrance, restlessness, is the last hindrance to go with conceit.

256
00:24:42,295 --> 00:24:48,105
Now, if we think of restlessness as simply

257
00:24:48,742 --> 00:24:52,352
just a form of energy being restless, then I don't think that's quite right.

258
00:24:53,053 --> 00:24:59,910
Restlessness is anything we feel, you see, which is actually shifting the mind.

259
00:25:00,009 --> 00:25:04,862
So it could be any of the hindrances which is making the mind shake.

260
00:25:05,702 --> 00:25:21,148
So if we look at the process of our practice as a refinement of the heart, a refinement of the mind, then all these hindrances just get more and more refined until they peter out, until they go out.

261
00:25:21,169 --> 00:25:22,592
They go out when the self disappears.

262
00:25:23,452 --> 00:25:27,440
So this restlessness is going to be with us right to the bitter end.

263
00:25:30,244 --> 00:25:31,727
So we've got to get used to it.

264
00:25:32,517 --> 00:25:46,172
so we've got to stop fighting it we've got to know how to be with it now when you're sitting there you see and the body feels tremendously restless so again you have to make a resolution you do exactly the opposite

265
00:25:46,539 --> 00:25:54,528
Even though there are these little nadas coming in saying, move, get up, get out, do something, shift, go take a walk, you'll feel better.

266
00:25:54,887 --> 00:25:56,349
See, all that sort of stuff.

267
00:25:56,369 --> 00:25:57,330
See, you don't move.

268
00:25:57,351 --> 00:25:59,252
It's absolute rock still, refuse to move.

269
00:26:00,334 --> 00:26:02,615
And as it were, relax around it.

270
00:26:02,635 --> 00:26:06,640
Relax the frame of the body around these feelings as best you can.

271
00:26:07,421 --> 00:26:09,843
And that sort of puts a damper on it, you might say.

272
00:26:10,824 --> 00:26:15,348
It just stops the energy beginning to shake everything.

273
00:26:15,598 --> 00:26:29,160
And if again you can just keep the mind moving, keep the mind moving around until you feel that you can hold it, as it were, then it'll keep that attention right on those feelings.

274
00:26:30,241 --> 00:26:34,468
And if again you investigate the body, parts of it don't feel restless at all.

275
00:26:35,430 --> 00:26:38,775
At the end of your nose, for instance.

276
00:26:38,795 --> 00:26:41,859
It's very rare at the end of your nose to feel restless.

277
00:26:42,750 --> 00:27:12,740
and then just to keep going around and again to see it from one of the three characteristics the quality of transience and all that and again to go into it and see what are the building blocks now remember that every time we go towards that point of contact where we're actually just experiencing the elements the four great elements heat, fire, water and earth pressure and all that remember at that point the intellect has to stop because you've got to be right with it there

278
00:27:13,345 --> 00:27:14,846
So we're seeing things very clearly.

279
00:27:15,347 --> 00:27:28,669
And at that point, because we've gone beyond the idea of restlessness, same with all the others, the idea of fear, the idea of sloth and torpor, then that energy, the suppression goes.

280
00:27:29,351 --> 00:27:35,319
Suppression only goes when you recognise something as pleasant and unpleasant.

281
00:27:35,619 --> 00:27:46,255
The suppressive forces, tanha, desire, wanting, not wanting, only comes into force after we've defined something as pleasant and unpleasant.

282
00:27:46,275 --> 00:27:53,144
If we go beyond that, into the actual feelings and lose that definition, then there's no suppression.

283
00:27:53,163 --> 00:27:58,692
That means that whatever that turbulence is, that restlessness, it's completely free to exhaust itself.

284
00:28:00,055 --> 00:28:05,240
And remember that when I'm using words like exhaust and expend and all that, the energy is not lost.

285
00:28:06,281 --> 00:28:09,506
It refines itself and is thereby to be used.

286
00:28:09,965 --> 00:28:12,828
Well, normally it comes back into the factors of enlightenment.

287
00:28:14,171 --> 00:28:24,762
The calm, the pacity, the calmness, the equanimity, the concentration, the effort, all that begins to get ironed out and reinforced, reinforced.

288
00:28:26,313 --> 00:28:34,203
So when we are working with restlessness in the body, so the big resolution is not to move.

289
00:28:35,905 --> 00:28:49,344
Now if you do walking meditation, again if the restlessness is severe, there's no point in doing a slow walking meditation because it's like you're trying to force a concentration on the step when the rest of the body is shaking like mad.

290
00:28:50,164 --> 00:28:51,527
So just walk up and down.

291
00:28:51,877 --> 00:28:53,740
It's like taking a frisky dog out for a walk.

292
00:28:54,080 --> 00:28:56,424
Just walk up and down and just stay with those feelings.

293
00:28:57,165 --> 00:29:00,431
And keep the attention moving and feeling it and just being with it.

294
00:29:00,711 --> 00:29:01,452
Take it for a walk.

295
00:29:02,614 --> 00:29:03,394
But do it gently.

296
00:29:04,718 --> 00:29:09,444
Don't start walking up and down like a mad person.

297
00:29:11,126 --> 00:29:12,269
Because that's just empowering it.

298
00:29:12,809 --> 00:29:19,539
So it's a case of just moving the body gently up and down and just letting these feelings express themselves.

299
00:29:20,666 --> 00:29:23,170
Again, remember that they've got a grudge against us.

300
00:29:23,931 --> 00:29:25,973
They need to get the grudge off their chest.

301
00:29:26,894 --> 00:29:27,275
Mara.

302
00:29:28,656 --> 00:29:29,258
Embrace them.

303
00:29:30,318 --> 00:29:30,778
Friends.

304
00:29:33,323 --> 00:29:34,804
I don't want to sound too new agey now.

305
00:29:36,026 --> 00:29:36,987
Huggy-wuggy normal.

306
00:29:45,196 --> 00:29:49,122
If the rest of us is in the mind, obsessive thinking,

307
00:29:49,912 --> 00:29:51,173
So what's happening there?

308
00:29:51,193 --> 00:29:52,154
What's happening you see?

309
00:29:52,895 --> 00:30:01,587
The old habit whereby an emotional state is seeking some sort of metaphor to work with.

310
00:30:01,607 --> 00:30:04,291
So the restlessness will grab anything it can be restless with.

311
00:30:05,232 --> 00:30:06,074
Doesn't matter what it is.

312
00:30:07,215 --> 00:30:16,407
And if you find that the mind is doing that then that's an avenue which has been conditioned to slip out into these higher faculties of thought and imagination.

313
00:30:17,214 --> 00:30:31,932
so if you try and kill that if you try and destroy it then of course again you're feeding aggression back into the system so we just have to be patient don't we very patient with it you just note it

314
00:30:32,098 --> 00:30:33,000
acknowledge it.

315
00:30:33,721 --> 00:30:37,848
I'm always for really acknowledging it.

316
00:30:38,509 --> 00:30:44,440
Sometimes we note something and it's more like a flip away, you know, restless, a little flick.

317
00:30:44,460 --> 00:30:47,444
And it's an aversion, you see, and we're not catching it.

318
00:30:47,464 --> 00:30:55,338
But if you actually note something, even if you don't use a word, just note it, restless, restless mind, obsessive thinking, and then

319
00:30:55,318 --> 00:31:17,917
the second one is like an acknowledgement like driving it home to ourselves that this is the restless mind and that stops that reaction of pushing it away or something and then just noting what it is and just come back come back into the body and again just feel if you can the restlessness which is empowering these thoughts

320
00:31:18,691 --> 00:31:43,550
at first you might not be able to feel it because the energy of that restlessness has that way out of exhausting its energy but if you keep doing it then slowly I think you'll find that you get in touch with that restlessness and that means that you're stopping that avenue of indulgence and the more these feelings come out through the body the more they're exhausting themselves

321
00:31:44,711 --> 00:32:02,821
so you can take that as an absolute rule until you prove me wrong that whenever these emotions slip into the higher faculties whether we have meant them to do so or not they are indulging themselves and they are growing

322
00:32:03,291 --> 00:32:15,102
I mean one obvious example of that is during the day at work or at home somebody says something which is a little upsetting and you just put it aside, you don't worry about it.

323
00:32:16,042 --> 00:32:24,971
And then when it comes to sort of morning break it slips up in the mind and while you're drinking your tea you're, how could they say anything like that to me?

324
00:32:24,990 --> 00:32:30,035
And then by lunchtime you're eating and you're, I'm pretty well told I'm not going to do that.

325
00:32:30,055 --> 00:32:32,978
And then by evening you're ripping them apart, throwing them out of windows.

326
00:32:34,425 --> 00:32:35,547
And you have to take Prozac.

327
00:32:38,730 --> 00:32:47,259
And all that's been done, not because you meant it to, because every time that there's a slippage into the fantasy world, it's developing the emotion.

328
00:32:47,279 --> 00:32:48,361
That's what the emotion wants to do.

329
00:32:49,482 --> 00:32:50,523
That's how it finds relief.

330
00:32:52,605 --> 00:32:55,088
If you're angry and you bang the door, there's a relief there.

331
00:32:55,249 --> 00:32:58,813
But unfortunately, we've reinforced the habit of being angry with doors.

332
00:33:05,509 --> 00:33:14,167
So with that obsessive thinking, it's just real, just constant persistence, just working with it.

333
00:33:14,548 --> 00:33:19,097
And every time the anger comes up, the fed upness comes up, all that, that's also to be noted.

334
00:33:19,659 --> 00:33:24,008
And just, as you know, after time, it fades out.

335
00:33:38,450 --> 00:33:42,615
I like these two hindrances, they often move from one to the other, don't they?

336
00:33:42,895 --> 00:33:45,659
You can be restless one minute and then you just fall asleep the next.

337
00:33:46,519 --> 00:33:48,461
And then you fall asleep and suddenly you can't stop moving.

338
00:33:49,403 --> 00:33:52,688
So there we see that actually all we're working with are forms of energy.

339
00:33:54,509 --> 00:33:58,755
The image I have is of an internal weather system.

340
00:33:58,775 --> 00:34:02,619
So the storms come, the whirlwinds, all that.

341
00:34:02,640 --> 00:34:06,684
And it's all the same thing, it just takes on a different hue, a different form.

342
00:34:11,356 --> 00:34:21,329
So those are some ideas about restlessness and again if you've got any little tricks up your sleeve and things like that or you think I've missed something out just leave me a note.

343
00:34:25,376 --> 00:34:30,963
The next thing that comes up isn't it apart from those two is just pain you know physical and mental pain.

344
00:34:36,010 --> 00:34:41,277
When it comes to physical pain that's just the nature of the body isn't it we can't stop that even the Buddha had pain

345
00:34:43,434 --> 00:34:48,844
So what we're concerned with is taking the suffering out of pain and we find that the suffering is simply our relationship to it.

346
00:34:50,385 --> 00:34:56,655
So when pain comes at least one good thing about it is that it does concentrate us.

347
00:34:58,679 --> 00:35:04,929
I'm sure there's often in our meditative lives when we are feeling very restless and all that that we are crying out for pain.

348
00:35:07,333 --> 00:35:08,514
It's just on a pin or something.

349
00:35:10,586 --> 00:35:22,161
And of course you have to be careful that you don't get, when it comes to physical pain, that you're clear that it's coming from the body and that the body is actually saying something.

350
00:35:22,402 --> 00:35:29,231
So obviously when we begin a retreat you can start getting these sore knees, screaming knees.

351
00:35:30,492 --> 00:35:35,699
So therefore you have to give them a bit of a stretch, give them a bit of a rest, have a bit of kindness towards your knees, things like that.

352
00:35:37,047 --> 00:35:43,914
But even so, it's an interesting thing for us because we are investigating that relationship we have with pain, which is aversion and fear.

353
00:35:45,876 --> 00:35:50,159
And the idea is not, of course, to overcome pain.

354
00:35:50,280 --> 00:35:53,782
We're not supposed to get macho with it, try to kill it, destroy it.

355
00:35:55,005 --> 00:36:01,170
But as soon as we lose that sense of the ability to investigate and to see our relationship to it, it becomes too much.

356
00:36:01,811 --> 00:36:03,713
Then you change posture.

357
00:36:04,164 --> 00:36:07,708
Now don't forget, when we change posture, there's a whole thing to be learned there.

358
00:36:08,489 --> 00:36:17,195
So here we are moving from a situation where the body is in pain and the mind is in pain, the emotions are in pain, aversion and all that.

359
00:36:17,876 --> 00:36:23,360
As we move slowly, the more slowly you go, the more you can see the connection between the body and mind.

360
00:36:24,101 --> 00:36:33,969
As you move slowly, you can see the sensations of pain fading out to neutral and you can see the heart moving from being very agitated to being calm, comfortable.

361
00:36:34,489 --> 00:36:44,503
So it's just watching that, watching that the mind-body, like the Buddha said, milk and water, they're constantly reacting off each other.

362
00:36:44,523 --> 00:36:48,387
So we're learning a few things there by just working with physical pain.

363
00:36:49,329 --> 00:37:01,105
And don't forget that the usual rule about physical pain is that if it carries on after a sitting or after walking, then go to see a doctor, because you never know.

364
00:37:01,894 --> 00:37:04,679
Generally speaking, as you know, these things disappear when you get up.

365
00:37:07,762 --> 00:37:21,860
But the other sort of pain, which is, I suppose, more interesting in a way, is the pain that comes from something suppressed in the body, some emotion that's, for want of a better word, blocked or held in a certain part of the body.

366
00:37:23,208 --> 00:37:36,043
And again, when those feelings come up, we're employing the same quality of seeing our relationship to it always and as that dies out to go into the pain to see what pain is made up of.

367
00:37:36,804 --> 00:37:46,476
Tightness, burning, whatever it is, just to get down to that level which makes it very clear that the idea of pain is a concept.

368
00:37:47,097 --> 00:37:48,539
It's something the mind works with.

369
00:37:49,447 --> 00:38:18,121
mind conceives it and of course there is a good reason for it we want to know when the body is in pain sometimes I think that we can become especially with physical pain I'm thinking now you can become a little insensitive to what the body is saying to us because we become so equanimous with it you have to be slightly careful about that

370
00:38:20,565 --> 00:38:34,543
I remember in my, because you can slightly overdo it, I had this occasion once when, actually as soon as I started meditating, I started getting this sort of discomfort in my neck, back of my neck here.

371
00:38:35,403 --> 00:38:36,826
And it grew and grew and grew.

372
00:38:36,865 --> 00:38:45,556
And I was at that time working with Goenkaji, with that system, you know, a few years ago now.

373
00:38:46,336 --> 00:38:50,202
And I went off by myself to his beautiful center in Jaipur.

374
00:38:50,806 --> 00:38:54,054
And he's built a castle there, or they built a castle there.

375
00:38:54,514 --> 00:38:55,858
And as you go in, it's a rotunda.

376
00:38:56,418 --> 00:38:59,186
And as you go in, there's all these little rooms on the outside and the inside.

377
00:39:00,007 --> 00:39:02,673
And they're all nice little rooms, you know, when you get in there.

378
00:39:03,735 --> 00:39:05,760
You do feel sort of supported by the walls.

379
00:39:07,686 --> 00:39:09,168
And this pain was...

380
00:39:09,605 --> 00:39:30,280
was really bad and I got into the habit of the idea in my head was that I was just going to squeeze it out of the system because I could feel it was in the musculature so I began sort of moving my head about like this and sort of stretching the muscles and eventually it got fairly sort of wild like this you see

381
00:39:30,800 --> 00:39:41,635
And over a period of 10 days, it was really what I would call the lower depths of hell.

382
00:39:43,239 --> 00:39:50,530
Often when I walked out and watched the little mice running here and running there.

383
00:39:52,130 --> 00:39:59,481
Anyway, when I got back to the UK, whenever I sat, my head would flop forward.

384
00:39:59,601 --> 00:40:02,385
I'd begin like this, but it would end up like this.

385
00:40:03,947 --> 00:40:17,108
It was only when somebody complained that there had been a group of monks at the Bihara I was staying at, maybe six or seven, and there were two Westerners

386
00:40:17,442 --> 00:40:45,170
amongst them and a friend came up and said to me that they were a little bit well ashamed is a bit too much that the only monks who fell asleep were the two westerners because I wasn't see I didn't say anything you know I wasn't I was like this you see so that propelled me to go and see the chiropractor and so when he's fiddling about with my head he told me that my skull had come off the top of my spine

387
00:40:47,293 --> 00:40:47,934
And I said, what?

388
00:40:50,918 --> 00:40:51,518
He said, it is.

389
00:40:52,280 --> 00:40:55,423
And then, you know, as they know, they get hold of your head, you know.

390
00:40:55,923 --> 00:40:59,367
And there was this 10,000 world almighty crack.

391
00:41:01,210 --> 00:41:02,851
It was alright, back on top of my spine.

392
00:41:03,773 --> 00:41:05,394
So, you see, you can take things too far.

393
00:41:05,416 --> 00:41:15,246
And I dare say that if I'd have carried on in that meditation centre, I might have beheaded myself.

394
00:41:15,266 --> 00:41:15,967
So,

395
00:41:16,706 --> 00:41:40,115
so you have to be slightly careful it's up to you really to gauge your own personality because if you're the timid type then you can push a bit but if you're the foolhardy type then well just watch your neck so

396
00:41:42,728 --> 00:42:03,246
When it comes to emotional pain remember that be very clear in your mind that the cause of it in terms of the external cause some fright that was given to you as a child or whatever it might be is not the root cause of that emotional state.

397
00:42:03,266 --> 00:42:07,831
The root cause is the conditioning which goes back to the self.

398
00:42:07,851 --> 00:42:12,195
Therefore, the memory, any memory which comes up is irrelevant.

399
00:42:12,360 --> 00:42:17,088
And this emotion of fear now will be chasing something to get hold of.

400
00:42:17,208 --> 00:42:26,179
So if the fear is there on the surface of your mind and you happen to be walking along and a spider jumps on you, then you end up with this arachnophobia for the rest of your life.

401
00:42:26,960 --> 00:42:31,047
So it's always searching for something by way of expressing itself.

402
00:42:31,146 --> 00:42:33,389
Well actually it's an indulging of itself.

403
00:42:33,978 --> 00:42:49,445
So by sitting with fear, by sitting with that pain in the body, even though we don't know what it is, it's only when, remember, these mental states hit the heart centre that we can begin to recognise them as emotions.

404
00:42:49,465 --> 00:42:54,315
Tightness in the belly, I mean you can call it anxiety but you don't know, it's just tightness in the belly.

405
00:42:54,733 --> 00:43:07,831
And so long as you get those feelings and the tightness in your body and the burning and all those peculiar things that come up and just to stay with them, you see, and treat them as physical pain.

406
00:43:08,472 --> 00:43:17,164
You go into it, you get into the feelings of it and just get the feeling of allowing it to blow its energy out.

407
00:43:17,362 --> 00:43:21,012
In the meantime, we're investigating these three characteristics.

408
00:43:21,032 --> 00:43:27,068
And in so doing, we are very slowly beginning to realize all the time that we are not that.

409
00:43:27,088 --> 00:43:28,672
We are not that.

410
00:43:33,748 --> 00:43:40,885
There's one last little story which goes with this from the Mahasi Centre.

411
00:43:41,146 --> 00:43:49,664
It's written in a book where all the healings that went on there over a period of so many years are sort of listed here.

412
00:43:50,708 --> 00:44:19,719
and there was one particular man who turned up with terminal cancer in the stomach and as he describes it he didn't take any medicine he was just going to work with it and sit there and die and as it goes as I remember it because I've not been able to get hold of this book since he was sitting there just watching the pain in the stomach and there was an explosion that's how he describes an explosion and the cancer disappeared

413
00:44:20,391 --> 00:44:27,625
Now, not all cancers are caused by emotional states, but in this case, lucky for him, it was.

414
00:44:27,945 --> 00:44:28,445
It disappeared.

415
00:44:28,987 --> 00:44:41,590
So, that's a very graphic example of what's actually happening when we allow these emotional states, which are in the body, are allowed to express themselves.

416
00:44:44,724 --> 00:44:45,166
Very good.

417
00:44:45,465 --> 00:44:52,994
So this evening we've covered just these three major ones, dullness and lethargy, restlessness and pain.

418
00:44:53,655 --> 00:44:57,179
And the next one I'll try and cover the rest.

419
00:44:58,179 --> 00:45:02,324
So I just wanted to spend just a bit of time on these questions.

420
00:45:02,344 --> 00:45:07,610
If I can't answer them all tonight, we can do so tomorrow.

421
00:45:11,184 --> 00:45:17,764
Please discuss concrete practical means of balancing concentration, energy and mindfulness.

422
00:45:20,110 --> 00:45:25,987
How to gauge what is needed without a sort of manipulation, that is with desire.

423
00:45:29,157 --> 00:45:35,646
When it comes to the spiritual faculties, which, of course, these are your three main ones, aren't they?

424
00:45:36,007 --> 00:45:39,331
Energy, awareness, concentration, concentration, energy, awareness.

425
00:45:41,835 --> 00:45:46,641
The Buddha makes it very simple for us.

426
00:45:47,543 --> 00:45:53,893
All he says is, if you pay attention to something, the other faculties will rise up to support it.

427
00:45:54,994 --> 00:45:58,860
So we don't have to worry about things like concentration and effort.

428
00:45:59,666 --> 00:46:03,992
As soon as you make the effort to be attentive that's enough effort you need.

429
00:46:04,653 --> 00:46:07,518
As soon as you're attentive that's enough concentration you need.

430
00:46:07,777 --> 00:46:17,650
You don't have to worry about these things.

431
00:46:17,690 --> 00:46:17,831
Okay.

432
00:46:17,891 --> 00:46:27,885
If you make a concentration an obsessive thing then you're missing out on the awareness because your attention is always on am I concentrated enough?

433
00:46:28,507 --> 00:46:38,922
If you're constantly worried about your energy and am I got enough energy for this then again your attention is moving off being attentive to being worried about whether you've got enough energy or not.

434
00:46:39,483 --> 00:46:45,411
But the fact of the matter is as soon as you are paying attention you have enough energy and concentration.

435
00:46:49,338 --> 00:46:57,670
And the more you keep placing the mind into that attentive mode then of course it just becomes sharper and sharper.

436
00:46:59,708 --> 00:47:03,733
So abandon concentration and energy.

437
00:47:06,416 --> 00:47:07,838
Just let the awareness do the trick.

438
00:47:10,762 --> 00:47:16,329
Remember that awareness is always coupled with intelligence.

439
00:47:16,349 --> 00:47:19,454
It has to be an awareness with a question mark.

440
00:47:19,474 --> 00:47:20,615
You can't be just aware.

441
00:47:21,556 --> 00:47:23,099
It has to be that wanting to know.

442
00:47:23,139 --> 00:47:26,322
And that's what empowers the system.

443
00:47:29,965 --> 00:47:34,429
What is the relationship of the Brahmaviharas to the Four Noble Truths?

444
00:47:36,974 --> 00:47:39,757
The Factors of Enlightenment and the Five Spiritual Faculties.

445
00:47:39,817 --> 00:47:46,005
Good heavens, there's nothing more to be talked about after we've been through this lot.

446
00:47:46,125 --> 00:47:49,369
What is the relationship of the Brahmaviharas to the Four Noble Truths?

447
00:47:50,610 --> 00:47:56,918
Well, it comes into right attitude.

448
00:47:57,724 --> 00:48:04,476
and it comes into right livelihood because your attitudes begin to express themselves in what you do.

449
00:48:06,438 --> 00:48:24,507
And to practice the brahmavihāras as Jānic states is all well and good in terms of developing our own mind but unless you can take those attitudes out into the world

450
00:48:25,552 --> 00:48:36,623
So, remember that the Buddha, he's constantly saying, whatever a teacher can do out of compassion for his students, I have done for you.

451
00:48:37,605 --> 00:48:49,838
So, his developments of the Brahmaviharas were presumably enormous, but they had to be expressed into an action.

452
00:48:50,239 --> 00:48:56,048
And the word he uses is ānu-kāṅpāṅ, ānu-kāṅpāṅ, which means to move towards the other.

453
00:48:56,869 --> 00:49:01,237
So, compassion, love and all these, they move you towards the other.

454
00:49:04,762 --> 00:49:05,784
That's the relationship.

455
00:49:06,625 --> 00:49:11,432
Now, of course, you don't need them to become enlightened, this is the point.

456
00:49:11,452 --> 00:49:16,820
These are the merits, these are your puṇya, this is what you get.

457
00:49:17,019 --> 00:49:20,762
as we move along the path of liberation.

458
00:49:23,025 --> 00:49:26,088
For liberation we're talking about a level of consciousness.

459
00:49:27,188 --> 00:49:29,010
We're talking about a way of looking.

460
00:49:30,072 --> 00:49:36,197
So this way of looking is directed through these three characteristics of existence.

461
00:49:36,217 --> 00:49:41,762
When we've looked in the right way one of the obvious insights we get is our interconnectedness.

462
00:49:42,503 --> 00:49:44,445
And when that interconnectedness

463
00:49:44,661 --> 00:49:57,717
is translated into a heart expression, when it moves into the heart as an expression, then it has to be love, compassion, sympathetic joy.

464
00:49:57,737 --> 00:50:03,583
If it just stays up here, well, it's not much cop.

465
00:50:03,603 --> 00:50:07,867
I'm reminded of an incident where a cat

466
00:50:08,422 --> 00:50:16,568
I was at a monastery and there was a cat and this cat was playing around with a mouse.

467
00:50:16,849 --> 00:50:18,670
It didn't want to eat it, it had been fed.

468
00:50:18,690 --> 00:50:20,172
It was just playing around with it.

469
00:50:20,932 --> 00:50:30,320
It had been, that's right, when I walked in there was a cat with a mouse and the mouse was dead and I said to the monk, I said, what happened here?

470
00:50:30,641 --> 00:50:31,963
He said, oh, he was just playing around with it.

471
00:50:32,583 --> 00:50:34,744
And I remember saying to him, well, didn't you stop it?

472
00:50:35,465 --> 00:50:36,706
He said, no, he calmed me.

473
00:50:37,632 --> 00:51:01,242
I was at another monastery when this cat sort of shot out and got a bird and this monk went up and gave it one hell of a wallop, took the bird out of its mouth, looked at it, realised that its lungs had been punctured and died, held it up very beautifully with its wings and chanted aniccavata sankara, you know, all compounded things arise and pass away.

474
00:51:03,028 --> 00:51:13,960
So now you see what this first monk didn't realise or didn't understand was that his seeing the cat is part of the cat's karma.

475
00:51:14,159 --> 00:51:19,565
The fact that he didn't react to the cat's cruelty is part of the cat's karma.

476
00:51:20,806 --> 00:51:33,018
And that's what I mean about it's alright talking about the interconnectedness of the universe and all that but if it doesn't express itself through a compassionate action then it's dead as a dodo.

477
00:51:39,817 --> 00:51:45,164
What does one do after leaving the anchor?

478
00:51:47,146 --> 00:51:51,612
I'm not so sure what that, I think that came up in an interview.

479
00:51:53,014 --> 00:51:58,983
It's not that you leave the anchor, like the breath is your anchor, it's a primary object.

480
00:51:59,523 --> 00:52:03,409
So the whole idea about the breath is that it's always there.

481
00:52:03,429 --> 00:52:05,992
I mean if it's not there, worry.

482
00:52:06,884 --> 00:52:28,773
so when everything calms down the mind becomes absolutely silent the body is absolutely still and the heart is completely in peace it's happened once or twice hasn't it then there is only the breath so now the breath is where you centre your whole attention and it's through the breath that these characteristics are seen

483
00:52:29,496 --> 00:52:51,242
And that's why it opens up in the Satipatthana discourse, the discourse on how to establish, because that's where you hone your skills, that's what you can always come back to, and eventually there is only the breath.

484
00:52:51,262 --> 00:52:56,347
Can you say something about the little thoughtlets which circumambulate, as it were, the primary object?

485
00:52:57,559 --> 00:53:02,188
Well, if they're only little thoughtlets, you see, just keep turning away.

486
00:53:02,208 --> 00:53:08,820
And as you're turning away, remember, you're drawing energy out of the system into the observing.

487
00:53:10,583 --> 00:53:13,690
You're actually drawing it out and putting it where it ought to be.

488
00:53:13,730 --> 00:53:17,255
So this is just a sort of mild restlessness, isn't it?

489
00:53:18,485 --> 00:53:22,010
And remember there are those two stages, vittaka and vichara.

490
00:53:22,610 --> 00:53:27,056
So the vittaka is when you are constantly bringing that focus back.

491
00:53:28,137 --> 00:53:29,179
Constantly bringing it back.

492
00:53:29,880 --> 00:53:32,463
You know the image of the bee flying towards the flower.

493
00:53:33,505 --> 00:53:37,230
And then the vichara is when finally the bee settles on the flower.

494
00:53:37,250 --> 00:53:40,954
So when you get that feeling of being settled on the breath.

495
00:53:40,974 --> 00:53:44,119
So those are signs of that concentration coming you see.

496
00:53:44,159 --> 00:53:45,740
Not that you are worrying about it.

497
00:53:46,547 --> 00:53:48,510
You're just worried about being attentive.

498
00:53:50,092 --> 00:53:51,675
And then there's that settling.

499
00:53:51,695 --> 00:53:57,822
So now that's a dangerous point because you tend to think, oh I'm finally there, brilliant.

500
00:53:57,842 --> 00:54:02,487
And you pull back a bit and off you go, the mind just bursts out because it's not really settled.

501
00:54:02,628 --> 00:54:11,559
You've got to keep working on that until there's a real sense of being absorbed into it, real steadiness, you know.

502
00:54:16,483 --> 00:54:21,489
How does one contemplate the three characteristics of existence without getting lost in concepts?

503
00:54:22,030 --> 00:54:30,240
So, in the discourse on how to establish this mindfulness, there are these three steps that the Buddha points out.

504
00:54:30,260 --> 00:54:32,824
He uses the word sikkati, which means to train.

505
00:54:33,304 --> 00:54:35,427
He says, train on the breath.

506
00:54:35,507 --> 00:54:41,775
Once you're settled, he says, see its quality of anicca, the quality of transience.

507
00:54:42,536 --> 00:54:43,757
And then he says,

508
00:54:43,737 --> 00:54:52,085
there comes a point when there is just enough sati, just enough awareness and just enough intelligence for insight to arise.

509
00:54:52,425 --> 00:54:54,208
At that point one isn't thinking anymore.

510
00:54:54,728 --> 00:55:00,434
You don't have to think because the intelligence, this intuitive intelligence has already been pointed that way.

511
00:55:02,157 --> 00:55:10,065
All we have to do by bringing up the idea in the mind of anicca, of transience, is you're directing your attention to a certain quality.

512
00:55:10,534 --> 00:55:17,365
Once it's directed to that quality and you begin to look at it, the thinking stops as you become absorbed in just looking.

513
00:55:18,467 --> 00:55:26,601
Remember the picture, for those of you who were here, that wonderful little baby with its eyes completely wide open and its jaw dropped.

514
00:55:28,605 --> 00:55:30,889
If you can get that feeling of just looking.

515
00:55:31,469 --> 00:55:34,855
And that's the point where...

516
00:55:36,117 --> 00:55:43,367
thinking and all that about the hindrances disappears because you're actually directly experiencing them.

517
00:55:43,387 --> 00:55:44,670
So those are the three stages.

518
00:55:45,130 --> 00:55:53,764
So you have to direct the mind and there's that question mark, that curiosity, the wanting to know, am I really seeing this the way it is?

519
00:55:54,565 --> 00:55:57,289
Have I really seen the quality of transience?

520
00:55:57,311 --> 00:56:03,340
Have I really seen the quality of not-self?

521
00:56:10,795 --> 00:56:18,221
He said, would it not be equally valid to follow the flow of breath sensations of the nose tip while doing walking meditation?

522
00:56:20,322 --> 00:56:21,123
You can do actually.

523
00:56:21,423 --> 00:56:24,385
It's more of a Samatha practice just to keep your mind on the breath.

524
00:56:29,050 --> 00:56:31,492
Make sure that you're walking in a very open space.

525
00:56:33,614 --> 00:56:38,277
You tend to walk into things when you do things like that.

526
00:56:38,297 --> 00:56:40,380
Just be aware of where you generally are.

527
00:56:44,157 --> 00:56:46,960
It says that walking meditation balances the faculties.

528
00:56:47,041 --> 00:56:50,105
Which faculties in particular does walking meditation balance?

529
00:56:50,525 --> 00:56:56,813
Well, as far as I remember, the normal thing is that what walking meditation is very good for is concentration.

530
00:56:58,295 --> 00:57:01,679
If you're worried about concentration, do the walking meditation.

531
00:57:01,699 --> 00:57:03,621
Because the walking meditation is gross.

532
00:57:03,802 --> 00:57:04,802
I mean, you can feel it.

533
00:57:04,864 --> 00:57:05,583
You're there with it.

534
00:57:06,445 --> 00:57:10,670
And you can use it to just keep your mind actually on the footstep.

535
00:57:11,393 --> 00:57:30,797
Now the balancing of the what's he say here the balancing of the faculties I mean presumably means the faculties of the facts of enlightenment or the five spiritual faculties again what balances those things is awareness attention that's what balances them.

536
00:57:30,817 --> 00:57:40,809
So walking meditation is very good for that if you you can actually do it in a way that you determine to stop whenever the mind wanders so you stop

537
00:57:42,038 --> 00:58:09,057
collect yourself intending to walk and off you go you don't have to turn around or anything but you stop every time the mind wanders I'll just do one last one oh well I've already answered that can you say more about sati combined with panya and where it's discussed in the suttas well that's in the main place is the discourse on how to establish awareness satipatthana

538
00:58:11,856 --> 00:58:13,219
Very good, I think that's enough for this evening.

539
00:58:14,822 --> 00:58:17,967
I hope that my words have been of some assistance.

540
00:58:17,987 --> 00:58:28,025
May you be fully liberated from all your suffering sooner rather than later.

